            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="23708301">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">As we will show, poor countries are poor because those who have power make choices that create poverty.  They get it wrong not by mistake or ignorance but on purpose.  To understand this, you have to go beyond economics and expert advice on the best thing to do and, instead, study how decisions actually get made, who gets to make them, and why those people decide to do what they do.  This is the s...</span>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2013-01-07 04:04</span>
                  
                    &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="">1人喜欢</span>
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                <blockquote><q>As we will show, poor countries are poor because those who have power make choices that create poverty.  They get it wrong not by mistake or ignorance but on purpose.  To understand this, you have to go beyond economics and expert advice on the best thing to do and, instead, study how decisions actually get made, who gets to make them, and why those people decide to do what they do.  This is the study of politics and political processes. ... [A]chieving prosperity depends on solving some basic political problems.  It is precisely because economics has assumed that political problems are solved that it has not been able to come up with a convincing explanation for world inequality.  Explaining world inequality still needs economics to understand how different types of policies and social arrangements affect economic incentives and behavior.  But it also needs politics.</q></blockquote><div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>
